DETAILED ITEMS

1. Core rules and required check order
- Check combined divisibility first (e.g., divisible by LCM of configured divisors). For two divisors 3 and 5, check n % 15 == 0 before checking n % 3 or n % 5.
- When generalising to more than two divisors, form token by concatenating tokens for all matched divisors in a predetermined rule order; or test for LCM(s) if a single combined token is required.

2. Procedural implementation pattern
- Input parameters: start (int), end (int), inclusive boolean, rules list (ordered), output sink (function or stream).
- Loop model: for n from start to end (inclusive if configured): evaluate rules, build token string, if token string is empty send decimal string else send token string.
- Streaming: pass each output to sink immediately. For in-memory use, append to list and return.

3. Generalised API and parameterisation
- Rules model: ordered list of rules. Each rule: divisor (positive int), token (string), optional matchOnDigit (bool).
- Precedence: rules earlier in list may determine concatenation order; all rules are evaluated for a number unless an early-exit policy is chosen.
- Optional flags: useDigitContainment (bool), digitContainmentPrecedence ("before_divisibility" | "after_divisibility"), joiner (string) to join multiple tokens.

4. Complexity and resource considerations
- Use modulus checks (n % divisor == 0). For many rules, optimize by skipping modulus when not necessary (e.g., maintain counters that decrement per iteration to avoid repeated modulus operations for fixed divisors).
- For extremely large ranges prefer generator/iterator interfaces to avoid O(N) memory use.

5. Variants and edge cases
- Zero: 0 is divisible by any non-zero divisor; decide whether to include 0 in sequence and handle accordingly.
- Negative numbers: modulus semantics vary by language; normalise or restrict domain to positive integers.
- Non-integer inputs: validate and reject or coerce before processing.

6. Best practices and testing
- Unit tests: verify outputs for sample ranges and rule sets. Cover boundary conditions (start==end, empty rules list, very large end).
- Property tests: for single-rule sets where token should appear exactly at multiples of divisor, assert positions.
- Performance tests: stream vs accumulate for large N; time per million items to validate streaming approach.
- Documentation: clearly specify default start/end and rule precedence in API docs.

